{"timestamp": "2025-12-12 04:52:18.061508", "event": "llm_end", "text": "**What we see**\n\n| Test | Result | What it tells us |\n|------|--------|------------------|\n| `host_1_1_1_1` → `dns_server (10.200.0.2)` | *Destination Host Unreachable* | The packet never leaves the host – the gateway 10.1.1.1 is not forwarding it. |\n| `host_1_1_1_1` → `10.1.1.1` | *Network is unreachable* | The host cannot even reach its own gateway. |\n| `host_1_1_1_1` → `10.1.1.1` (again) | *Network is unreachable* | Same as above – the host’s routing table is not being used. |\n\n**Where the problem is**\n\n* `host_1_1_1_1` has IP **10.1.1.21** and a default gateway of **10.1.1.1**.  \n* The device at 10.1.1.1 is **router_dist_1_1**.  \n* `router_dist_1_1`’s `br0` interface is correctly configured as **10.1.1.1/24** – it is the gateway for the 10.1.1.0/24 subnet.  \n* However, its routing table contains a **bogus** entry:\n\n```\n10.200.0.0/24 dev br0\n```\n\n  This tells the router that the 10.200.0.0/24 network is *directly* attached to its `br0` interface (which is 10.1.1.1). In reality, 10.200.0.0/24 lives on the server’s `br0` (10.200.0.1). Because the router thinks the network is local, it never forwards packets to it – they are dropped, and the host sees “Destination Host Unreachable”.\n\n* The “Network is unreachable” when pinging 10.1.1.1 from the host is a side‑effect of the same mis‑routing: the host’s ARP for 10.1.1.1 fails because the gateway is not reachable (the router is not forwarding the ARP reply).\n\n**Root cause**\n\nA **routing mis‑configuration on `router_dist_1_1`** – the router has an incorrect static route that marks the 10.200.0.0/24 network as directly connected, when in fact it is not. Because of this, the gateway never forwards traffic to the DNS server (10.200.0.2) or even to its own IP, causing the host to report “Network is unreachable”.\n\n**What to check next**\n\n1. Verify that the physical/virtual link between `router_dist_1_1` and the server actually exists (e.g., a link on `eth6` or `eth7` that should carry 10.200.0.0/24 traffic).  \n2. Remove or correct the bogus `10.200.0.0/24 dev br0` entry in `router_dist_1_1`’s routing table.  \n3. Ensure that the server’s `br0` (10.200.0.1) is reachable from `router_dist_1_1` via the correct interface (likely `eth6` or `eth7`).  \n4. After fixing the route, test `ping host_1_1_1_1 → 10.200.0.2` again – it should succeed.\n\nOnce the router’s routing table reflects the real topology, the host will be able to reach the DNS server and the “Network is unreachable” error will disappear.", "generation_info": {"model": "gpt-oss:20b", "created_at": "2025-12-12T04:52:17.254125647Z", "done": true, "done_reason": "stop", "total_duration": 32134814383, "load_duration": 67095028, "prompt_eval_count": 8097, "prompt_eval_duration": 6944865023, "eval_count": 2581, "eval_duration": 24794227102, "model_name": "gpt-oss:20b"}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8097, "output_tokens": 2581, "total_tokens": 10678}}
